The Chief Executive Officer of the First Bank Nigeria Limited, Dr. Adesola Adeduntan, has asked students to imbibe the financial institution’s value orientation. Dr. Adeduntan gave the charge while addressing students of the Methodist Girls’ High School, Yaba on the First Bank’s values-promoting initiative, ‘Start Performing Acts of Random Kindness’ (SPARK) as part of the activities marking the third edition of FirstBank’s Corporate Responsibility and Sustainability in Lagos. According to the First Bank’s Managing Director, aside the fact that imbibing the spirit of SPARK helps in developing one’s skills, it  also helps in improving mental health, living a value-centred life that build and achieve goals and objectives. OVER 5,000 NIGERIAN MEN HAVE  OVERCOME POOR BEDROOM PERFORMANCE SYNDROME DUE TO THIS BRILLIANT DISCOVERY. CLICK HERE TO KNOW MORE Represented by the Bank’s Group Head, Retail Banking, Lagos Island 1, Mrs. Olufunke Smith, the First Bank MD said SPARK is also a strategic approach to developing businesses as consumers tend to relate well with firms that have their concerns in mind. First Bank marks 125th anniversary, reassures commitment to Nigeria’s development Lack of savings can cause hyperinflation - FBN MD Experts explore Sustainable  Agro-Devt  at First Bank Agric show Dear Esteemed reader, As part of our drive to keep improving the content of our newspaper, we are conducting a readership survey to enable us serve you better. Kindly take two minutes of your time to fill in this questionnaire. Thank you for your time. Click here to begin